Let's find the limit as $x$ approaches $4$ from the right. We will use the fact that $f(x)=8\sqrt{x}$ for $x$-values greater than $4$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4^+}f(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4^+}8\sqrt{x}
\\\\
&=8\sqrt{4}&\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=16
\end{align}$

Let's find the limit as $x$ approaches $-2$ from the left. We will use the fact that $h(x)=\dfrac{1}{2x}$ for $x$-values smaller than $-2$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^-}h(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^-}\dfrac{1}{2x}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{2(-2)}&\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac14
\end{align}$

Let's find the limit as $x$ approaches $-3$ from the left. We will use the fact that $f(x)=\sqrt{7+x}$ for $x$-values smaller than $-3$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -3^-}f(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -3^-}\sqrt{7+x}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{7+(-3)}&\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=2
\end{align}$

Let's find the limit as $x$ approaches $-4$ from the right. We will use the fact that $f(x)=2^x$ for $x$-values greater than $-4$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -4^+}f(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -4^+}2^x
\\\\
&=2^{-4}&\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{16}
\end{align}$

Let's find the limit as $x$ approaches $-1$ from the left. We will use the fact that $g(x)=e^x$ for $x$-values smaller than $-1$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1^-}g(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1^-}e^x
\\\\
&=e^{-1}&\gray{\text{Direct substitution}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{e}
\end{align}$
